hands_on_practices.solution:
MHC Class I genes exhibit codominant expression: for each locus, both alleles in a diploid individual are transcribed and translated, and each distinct allele at that locus produces a distinct heavy chain protein that associates with the invariant beta-2 microglobulin. Therefore, at a given locus:
- If the individual is homozygous, the two gene copies are identical and yield one distinct protein for that locus.
- If the individual is heterozygous, the two gene copies are different and yield two distinct proteins for that locus.

Let $n_{L}$ denote the number of distinct HLA Class I heavy chain proteins produced from locus $L \in \{A,B,C\}$. Then, by the codominant expression principle,
$$
n_{A}=\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if homozygous at HLA-A,}
\end{cases}
\quad
n_{B}=\begin{cases}
2 & \text{if heterozygous at HLA-B,}
\end{cases}
\quad
n_{C}=\begin{cases}
2 & \text{if heterozygous at HLA-C.}
\end{cases}
$$
The total number of distinct classical MHC Class I proteins on nucleated cells is the sum over loci because each locus encodes a distinct gene product:
$$
N=\sum_{L \in \{A,B,C\}} n_{L}=n_{A}+n_{B}+n_{C}=1+2+2=5.
$$
Assuming full expression of all alleles, this yields five distinct HLA Class I proteins (HLA-A: one type; HLA-B: two types; HLA-C: two types).
